<editorial_guidelines>
PLAN EXACTLY 12 articles for today. Fixed composition:
- EXACTLY 10 news (type="news"): breaking/current Portuguese news relevant to Ukrainians
- EXACTLY 1 material (type="material"): in-depth compiled article from multiple sources (immigration, housing, healthcare, taxes, etc.)
- EXACTLY 1 guide (type="guide"): practical how-to guide (documents, benefits, procedures, etc.)
Do not substitute other types. The digest (evening TG post) shows ONLY news; material and guide live on the site and are surfaced via "Читайте також" blocks.

RULES:
1. DO NOT repeat topics from the last 30 days (see recent articles above)
2. DO NOT repeat topics already written today
3. Prioritize: breaking news > utility alerts > immigration updates > economy > society > culture
4. Each article must have a SPECIFIC angle, not just a general topic
5. Material articles need compilation from 3+ sources — specify what to search for
6. Cover geographic diversity: not just Lisbon, also Porto, Faro, Algarve when relevant
7. Include at least 1 article directly useful for daily life (transport, weather, prices, deadlines)
8. Include at least 1 immigration/AIMA/SEF topic if there's news
9. Day of week matters: Monday = week outlook, Friday = weekend plans, etc.
10. FOLLOW-UPS: If a story from the past 30 days has NEW DEVELOPMENTS, include it as a follow-up. Mark these with "(continuation)" in the topic. The article will reference our previous coverage.

EXCLUSIONS (zero tolerance — drop article if it falls into these):
E1. NO international politics. Only Portuguese politics (government, parliament, parties, elections, ministries, municipalities). Foreign elections, wars, summits, leaders abroad — DROP.
E2. NO international news (events outside Portugal). Exception: ONLY if directly affects Ukrainians in Portugal (e.g. Ukraine policy that changes diaspora rights, EU rules applied in PT).
E3. NO sports. Exception: ONLY if it affects residents' daily life (closed roads for marathon, public transport for a major match, stadium construction impact). No match results, no transfers, no league standings.
E4. NO crime news. No murders, robberies, accidents, court cases. Leave crime for other outlets. Exception: ONLY systemic stories that change rules/laws affecting residents (e.g. new anti-fraud law, immigration scam warnings).

BALANCE (critical):
11. MAX 1 article per narrow topic (weather, transport, weekend events are DIFFERENT topics — but "storms" and "weather forecast" are the SAME topic, merge them into one)
12. EXACTLY 1 material + 1 guide + 10 news (non-negotiable). No utility type — merge any utility angle into news.
13. Spread categories across 10 news: Portuguese politics, economy, immigration, society, culture, practical life. At least 5 different categories.
14. If you have 2+ articles about similar themes (e.g. weather + storms, or metro + transport), MERGE them into one comprehensive article.
15. SELF-CHECK before outputting: count articles per category. If any category has 3+, remove the weakest and replace with an underrepresented category.

STRICT DEDUPLICATION (zero tolerance):
16. WEATHER: Maximum ONE weather article per day. If there are storms, dust, heat, warnings — combine EVERYTHING into one comprehensive weather article. Never split "forecast" and "warnings" into separate articles. Weather is a utility, not news — keep it concise.
17. TRANSPORT DISRUPTIONS: If a strike/disruption was already covered (see recent articles), do NOT write "it's happening now" or "day-of report" — that's a duplicate, not news. Only write a NEW article if there is genuinely new information (new dates, negotiations failed, new alternatives). Simply confirming what was already announced is NOT new info.
18. SAME EVENT, DIFFERENT DAY: If we published "X will happen tomorrow" yesterday, do NOT publish "X is happening today" — the reader already knows. Wait for new developments or aftermath.
19. TOPIC OVERLAP with recent 7 days: Before planning ANY article, check recent_articles_last_30_days. If the SAME phenomenon (dust, storms, strike, price hike) was covered in the last 3 days, you MUST have a genuinely different angle. "Updated numbers" or "new city affected" alone are NOT sufficient — merge into the existing coverage or skip.
20. SELF-CHECK DEDUP: After drafting the plan, review each article against: (a) other articles in today's plan, (b) articles from yesterday, (c) articles from 2 days ago. For each pair that shares >30% of the same facts/sources, MERGE or DROP one.
</editorial_guidelines>